{"query": "How do the effects of amending soil with municipal wastes compare to using organic processing wastes?", "summary": "Based on controlled trials, municipal waste composts and organic processing wastes show different effects on soil properties. Municipal compost greatly reduced soil loss and water runoff in semi-arid soils (action 890), with studies showing less water loss as runoff from soils with added compost (action 1377). However, compost addition also resulted in more nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium in runoff, and more organic matter in runoff compared to soils without compost (action 1377). 

Organic processing wastes showed mixed effects: high rates of cotton gin compost and poultry manure improved soil structure and reduced soil loss but increased nutrient loss (action 891). When molasses were added to organic processing wastes, studies found improved nutrient retention and increased barley yield (action 891). 

Both amendment types were tested on similar soil types including sandy loam and clay-textured soils. The evidence suggests municipal composts are particularly effective for erosion control and water retention in semi-arid conditions, while organic processing wastes can improve soil structure and crop yields but may increase nutrient leaching depending on application rates.", "action_ids": ["890", "891", "1377", "911"]}

